{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_coldplay_ver02/data/sn83007654/00393342778/1907121301/0211.xml":{"full_text":"I The Spriugszbe News\u00ab\n21st YEAR-NO, 32\nSF\u2019RIIIGDALE, WASHINGTON COUNTY, ARKANSAS. FRIDAY, DECEMBER 13, 1907\nTWELVE PAGES\nIu the Town ancl Countv.\nIB\nTell them vou saw the ad. in\nThe News.\nA daughter was born to Mr.\nand Mrs. J. W. Curtis on Tuesday\nof last week.\nShore Searcy spent first of the\nweek visiting with friends in\nEureka Springs.\nBob Breeding was transacting\nbusiness at Westville, Oklahoma,\nhrst of the week.\nGeo- H. Brown orders The\nNews sent to his brother, Hi\nram Brown, at Cookville, Tenn.\nUncle Henry Abbott orders\nThe News sent to his cousin,\nDaniel Abbott, at l\u2019ortersville,\nCalifornia.\nDrilling for oil still goes on,\nthe hole now being down to a\ndepth of 809 feet, still going\nthrough limestone.\nArthur Watson sends The\nNews a dollar from Portersville,\nCalifornia, and orders the paper\nsent to his address.\nMr. and Mrs. H. S. Cuplin, of\nIowa Falls. Iowa, arrived\nWednesday and will probably\nmake Springdale their home.\nA daughter was born to Mr.\nand Mrs. H. E. Bennet, residing\nnear the grammar school building\non Tuesday night of last week.\nThe News will cheerfully ac\ncord space to all local ministers j\nfor any announcements they may!\nwisli to make regarding their\nservices.\njonn liiase. accompanied u\\\nhis brother Ellwood, who resides\nover on War Eagle, leit Monday\ntor Hot Springs to spend a couple\nof weeks.\nMrs. Frank White and children\nleft yesterday afternoon for\nNorth Carolina where the former\nlias relatives. They may prob\nably spend the winter there.\nPeople are coming from far\ndistant jjoints to do their trad\ning in Springdale. And the best\nof it all is they go awav well\npleased and tell their neighbors\nabout it.\nMrs. I). M. Simpson, of Coal\ngate, Oklahoma, sister of Mrs.\nJohn Wasson, residing west of\nSpringdale, who had been here\non a visit, left for home Wednes\nday morning.\nft\nMr. and Mrs. G. Dodson ex\nect to leave to-morrow (Satur\n|ay) for San Antonio, Texas, to\nlend the winter with Mr. and\nfs. Lou Nickerson, the latter\ntheir daughter.\nI'.he Presbyterian ladies will\nI serve a hot dinner in the Gillett\nbuilding near the Stone Livery\nBarn on Saturday, the 21st, and\nin the afternoon will conduct a\nI bazaar and serve tea.\nWill Carter. Jim Van Horn and\n(lertie Parrott went over to West\nville, Oklahoma, Monday to\nwork, J. W. Carter having the\n:ontract for a number of\n(buildings at that place.\nMrs. H. B. Hopkins, who had\n|>een up visiting with relatives\nind friends out near Elm Springs\n|ook the train here Wednesday\nlorning for her home at Morrow\ni the west part of the county.\nRev. and Mrs. J. F. Palmer\n|ecently moved to their newly\ninstructed home south of towm,\nInd Mr. and Mrs. Harry Buvk j\nave moved into the G. P- Eidson 1\nroperty on Johnson Street va\nited bv them.\nLeda, little daughter of Mr.\nid Mrs. W. A. Graves, has been\nitically ill for the past week\n[ith diptheria, but yesterday\nle was reported as improving,\nfbe infant son of Mr. and Mrs.\nI\nGraves also lias an attackof the\nsame disease, but is likewise im\nproving. l)r. Henderson,of lm\nboden. an uncle of Mr\\ iiraves,\nwas called first of the w>el< otid\nleft for his home ^efriesday\nnight.\nW. L. Stokes, who eeently\ntraded for the Chewniig resi\ndence property in the eastoart of\ntown, has made sonu ijprove\nments on same and moved his\nfamily in Wednesday aid will\nmake it their home.\nw. G. Tompson left Monday\nevening for Chicago on business,\nand C. N. Furry went along\n\u201cjust to be going somewhere.\u2019*\nThey may probably take motion\nto settle the financial panic while\nthey are up there.\nThe News would be pleised to\ngive space next week to the pro\ngrams for Christmas exercises at\nthe different churches, but re\nquests those interested to kindly\nget the copy in not later than\nWednesday morning.\nFelix Hayes announces in this\nissue of The News as a candidate\nfor re-election to the officeot tax\nassessor of Washington Countv.\nFelix has servedonlyone term.and\nwill likely have no sppoitiou. He\ndeserves a re-election and will\nget it.\nur. anu Airs. j. ty. .Martin\nwere over from Hindsville first\nof the week. Dr. Martin informs\nThe News that their bank will\nbe opened as soon as they receive\nsome additional supplies that\nhave been delayed. The >atV i^\nnow in place.\nJ. Summers, of Benton Harbor.\nMich., who has been here through\nthe season assisting C. II. God\nfrey it Son in the canning fac\ntory, left for home yesterday.\nHe remained over after the de\nparture of Mr. Godfrey tocom\nplete some labeling and packing.\nMrs. M. K. Fugate returned\nThursday of last week from a\nvisit with her sister, Mrs. Lou\nJameson, at Ninnekah. Oklaho\nma. Mrs. Fugate had not seen\nher sister for about eighteen\nyears, and naturally her visit\nwas one of much pleasure to\nboth.\nT. C. Glover, living out about\nElm Springs, returned Tuesday\nnight from Seymour, Texas,\nwhere he had been to accom\npany his mother, who willl visit\nwith her daughter down there\nfor some time, Mr. Glover re\nturned byway of 1 furant, Okla\nhoma.\nJudge and Mrs. A. L. Tlion.5\u2022\nson leit Saturday morning for\nDeOueen, and after visiting with\ntheir son Floyd at that place\nwill go on to Pollok, Texas, to\nvisit wiih Mr. and Mrs. All\nPrater. They expect to be ab\nsent until about the first of Feb\nruary.\nMrs. Minnie Scott, of Marsh\nfield, Mo., son of Mr. and airs.\nJohn Steinberg, who formerly\nresided in Springdale, arrived\nThursday of last week to spend\na couple of weeks visiting with\nrelatives here. She is a sister of\nMrs J. W. Goree and Mrs. Joh'1\nKelley.\nMrs. Emily Beard, wife of Tn\ncle Gy Beard, living near Goad\nSprings, Benton county, died\nat 11 a. m. Monday of pneumon\nia after an illness of only about\nne week. The remains fcere >n\u2018\nterred in the cemetery at Goad\nSprings Tuesday afternoon at\ntwo o'clock, services being ^)n'\nducted by Kevs. W. F. Green\nand W. C. Hamby. Deceased\nhad long been a resident of that\nsection and was held in high es\nteem bv a large circle ol friends.\nBesides an aged husband, deceas\ned is survived by a number of\nchildren and grand children, one\nof her sons being J. M. Beard,\nour Lowell correspondent.\nWednesday afternoon some one\nfired a 22-calibre rifle ball\nthrough a window7 at the resi\ndence of L. Marks on Maple\nStreet. It was probably done by\nsome careless boy, and emphasiz\nes the necessity of being very\ncareful in the handling and dis\ncharge of fire arms.\nA little child, one of the fam\nily living in the old Pollock\nproperty on Holcomb Street, died\nTuesday night of diptheria.\nThis and the two cases in the\nfamily of W. A. Graves, are the\nonly ones in town so far as\nknown, and no fears are enter-1\nI\ntained of the disease spreading, j\nG. P. Roberts sends The News\na dollar from Oakland, Calitor-!\nnia to renew his subscripiion,\nand orders his address changed\nto 988 5bth street. Geno com-\nplains of not having received a j\ncopy of the paper for seven\nweeks, but we have sure been\nmailing it from this office every\nweek.\nme *>c\\*>K* in rcLCipi ui v\ncopy of tin* Lincoln Times, giv\ning an account of a program ren\ndered by the students of the\npublic school at that place on\nThanksgiving night. The ar\nticle speaks very highly of the\nwork of the teachers, one of\nwhom is Miss Mary Curtis Cald\nwell. ol this place.\nAttention is directed to the\nstatement of the condition of tin*\nFirst National Bank of Spring\ndale appearing in this issue.\nThese statemants are made on call\nof the Comptroller of the Currency\nand every National bank in the\nUnited States is called on at the\nsame time and are required to\nmake public a statement of their\ncondition. The showing of the\nFirst National is quite creditable.\nJames E. Lester, who resides\nnear Mt. Comfort in Prairie\nTownship, announces this week\nas a candidate for the legislature.\nMr. Lester is a native of Arkan- I\nsas, and has been a resident of\nWashington County for ten years.\nI* or five years he was engaged in\ntidiness at Fayetteville, and isnow\nengaged in farming. He is a\nyoung man of pleasing appear\nance and is well spoken of by j\nthoes who know him.\nMr. and Mrs. A. D. Baggett,\nliving north of town, sold from\none cow from April 2 to Decem\nber 2, eight months, 2\u2018H pounds\nof butter, in addition to what the\nfamily consumed at home.\nEvery pound of butter they sold\nbrought them 2'> cents in cash,\na total of $58.20, for the eight\nmonths. They must have a\nmighty good cow or Mrs. Bag\nget is an extra good hand to\nlook after the milk and butter,!\nprobably both.\nThe music pupils of Miss Ruth\nWirt gave a recital at her home\non Saturday evening, which was\ngreatly enjoyed by the invited\nguests, and reflected much credit\non both pupils and teacher.\nThose taking part in the pro\ngram were Esther Wirt, Monnie\nPhillips, Upah Massey, Fla Old\nham, Clara Ewalt, Annie Old\nham, Ida Evans and Joye Lang\nston. A recitation by Anna\nRitter lent variety to the pro\ngram, and w\u2019as also highly enjoy\ned. Another recital will be giv\nen soon after the holidays.\nWtn. Martin returned Thurs\nday of last week from a months\nvisit with relatives and friends\nin Missouri and Kansas. While\naway he visited at Washburn,\nRepublic, Hutnansville and\nKansas City, Mo., and Atchison.\nFrankfort. Howe City, Heattie\nand Vermillion, Kansas. He\nformerly lived near Frankfort,\nand it was here that he and .Mrs.\nMartin were married forty-eight\nyears ago. Tliet moved from\nthere forty-one years ago. Nat\nurally Mr. Martin found many\nchanges had taken place since\nlie left. About the only thing\nleft was the old well which he\ndug when a young man. and\nagain he had the pleasure of\ndrinking the water from its\ndepths, probably for the last\ntime. Mr. Martin reports an\nenjoyable time at all the points\nhe visited.\nThe News had intended issu\ning the regular Christmas num\nber next week and give space to\nthe children\u2019s letters to Santa\nClaus, but on account of the ex\ntra amount of work that has\nbeen necessary in the office the\npast two weeks we have found it\nnecessary to abandon the Christ\nmas number for this year, which\nalso means that we will not have\nspace for the Santa Claus letters.\nNo one regrets this more than\nthe publisher of the paper, but\nthere are limits to human endur\nance and the capacity of all news\npaper offices, and we have reach\ned the limit around this office the\npast two weeks and it would not\nbe just to the force to burden it\nwith the extra work necessary to\nget out a Christmas number.\nHowever, with this issue and\nnext we give our readers some\nspecial articles that breathe of\nthe Season's good cheer.\nIn this issue of The News will\nbe found the announcement of\nD, If. Horsley, of Bentonville. as\na candidate for prosecuting at\ntorney of the Fourth judical cir\ncuit. subject to the action of the\nDemocratic primary. Mr. Horsley\nis the present prosecuting attorn\ney, having been appointed to the\nposition by the governor June 20.\nl\u2018K)5. to fill out the unexpired\nterm of Judge Maples. At the\nDemocratic primary in March,\n1 he was a candidate before\nthe people, being opposed by C.\nM. Rice of Bentonvtlle, and his\njropularity is attested by the fact\nthat he carried every county in\nthe district. Mr. Horsley\u2019s friends\nthink he is entitled to a second\nterm, although he is not making\nthe race on that issue. In his work\nas prosecuting attorney Mr.\nHorsley\u2019s motto has been a fair,\nreasonable and just enforcement\nof all the laws against all alike.\nMr. and Mrs. 1. I>. Rader re\nturned recently from a three\nweeks visit with relatives in\nWebster county, Mo., and Mr.\nRader tells The News that lie\nfound more kinsfolk up there\nthan he had ever before heard of\nThey were visiting' with the de\nscendants of Joseph Rader, an un\ncle of Mr. Rader. He died Mav\n7, 1X07, at the age of 74 years,\nhaving- been married twice, his\nsecond wife, who survives him,\nbeing a sister of Mrs. I. I). Ra\nder. Mr. Rader was the father\nof IX children, 15 of whom are\nliving-. There are 100 grand\nchildren, 07 of whom are living,\nand 76 great grand-children, bb\nof whom are living. They all\nreside in Webster county, in the\nvicinity of Rader, a postoffice\nnamed for Mr. Rader. Mr. Ra\nder says they are a lively, jolly,\npeople, and he and his wife had a\nmost enjoyable time among them.\nDr. R. W. Douthat will lecture\nat the Auditorium to-night\n(Friday) at 7:30 on the battle of\nGettysburg. lie lectured at\nFayetteville last night under the\nauspices of the Daughters of the\nI Confederacy, and comes to\nI Springdale at the request of a\nProspects Good for Electric\nLight Plant in Springdale.\nIt is thought by every one that\nSpringdale now has the best op\nportunity for securing electric\nlights that the town has ever\nhad\n(i. C. Martin, of the firm of M.\nC. G. C. Martin, contracting\nelectricians of Cleveland, Ohio,\nwithwhomDr. Smith, presidentof\ntheCitizens League, has been in\ncorrespondence for some time,\narrived Monday night to look\nover the field. After interview\ning the people here and looking\nover the town lie was very favor\nably impressed, and applied to\nthe town for a franchise. At a\nspecial meeting of the council\nWednesday morning the ordi\nnance granting the franchise was\ncarefully gone over, all the mi\nnor details arranged, and a reso\nlution was adopted pledging the\ncouncil to the passage of the or\ndinance at the next regular meet\ning, which will be the first Tues\nday night in January.\nAs agreed upon, the ordinance\ngrants the Springdale Electric\nLiget and Power Company a\nfranchise for a term of twenty\nfive years. The rates for busi\nness houses will be o() cents per\nmonth for lo-candle power lights,\nand JO cents lor residences, the\nminimum being SI.20. Meters\nwill also he put in where desired,\nthe minimum meter rate being\nSI.00 per month. These prices\nare very reasonable, and the\ncouncil also secured good rates for\nstreet lighting. The prices\nare for a service from dusk until\nmidnight\nThe company is given ninety\nnumber oi our citizens who desire\nto hear him but were unable to at\ntend his lecture at Fayetteville.\nDr. Douthat was a captain in the\nConfederate army, and out of\neleven captains in his regiment\nhe was the only one who survived\nPickett's famous charge. He\ncomes highly recommended as\nan interesting speaker, and his\nlecture to-night will be a treat\nsuch as is seldom heard in Spring\ndale. In order to defray the ex\npenses of the lecture a small ad\nmission of 25 cents will be\ncharged. No one should fail to\nattend, and hear the thrilling\nstory of one of the greatest bat\ntles of the Civil War as told by\nan eye witness.\nThe advertising campaign\nwhich is being carried on by\nSpringdale merchants is bearing\nfruit, as attested by the splendid\ntrade that they are enjoying.\nLast Saturday probably broke all\nprevious records as to the quanti\nty of goods sold in this town in\nany one day. and the fact that it\nwas praticcally all cash business\ngoes to show that this portion\nof the country at least is not suf\nfering from any financial panic.\nMost of the merchants had pro\nvided extra salesmen and then it\nwas not possible to wait on the\ntrade. The Springdale Cash\nDry (loods Company employed\nthe iilack Diamond Orchestra of\nFayetteville for the occasion,\nwhich furnished music through\nlout the day and evening. Long\niV Snider introduced an innova\ntion by distributing free a quan\ntity of merchandise. The goods,\ntogether with a lot of pennies,\nwere thrown front the top of their\nbuilding at 1:30 p. m., and a\nlarge crowd of people were con\ngregated in the street below,\npartly to witness the proceedings\nand to share in the general pros\n.days in whit h to began work ana\n[eight months to complete th\nI plant. The council also gav>\nthem the privilege of using th*\nI brick buihling on the Auditor*\nium grounds, and in this will b>\nlocated the engine and generator.\nIn conversation with Thr\nNews Mr. Martin says they ex\npect to put in a first-class, up-to\ndate plant and one that will\nrender good service. They wilj\ni put in a seventy-five horse power\nj engine and a hundred horse\nboiler, giving them a capacity of\n1,000 lights, and as the business\ngrows they will increase their\ncapacity acccordingly. Although\nthey heve beengiven three months\nin which to begin work. Mr.\nMartin says they will in all\nprobability be here within sixty\ndays ready to contract for light\ning. In wiring the houses the\nconsumers will have to pay\nfor what is inside\nthe house, and then only the act\nual cost. Where meters are in\nstalled the company also pays\nthe expense.\nTaken altogether the contract\nseems to be a very advantageous\none for flic town, and the action\nof the coun* il will ho doubt meet\nwith the approval of the entire\npeople. Mr. Martin left for his\nhome this morning. He made a\nvery favorable impression on all\nwho met him, and they have con\nfidence that lie will carry out his\n[contract. He informs The News\nthat probably faith he and his\nbrother will bring their families\nto Springdale and make this their\nhome.\nperity. It furnished great fun\nfor awhile, and those who failed\nto secure any of the goods seem\njed to enjoy the sport equally\nwith their more fortunate neigh\nbors. The merchants here are\nstill continuing their low-price\nsales, and again The News urges\nall to come to Springdale to do\ntheir trading while this oppor\ntunity lasts.\nAMONG THE CHURCHES.\nMethodist Episcopal Church\nSoitth. Preaching- every Sun\nday; hours, 11 a. ni. and 7 p. m\nSunday School *>:45\nSubjects for next Sunday.\u201411\na. in., \u201cLordship of hrist;\u201d 7 p.\ntil., \u201cPassing the Rubicon.\u201d\nli. Walt hr Lkdhettkr,\nPastor.\nChristian Church. Preach\ning next Sunday, morning and\nevening by the pastor. Rev. H.\nS. Mobley.\nOAK GROVE.\nDec. 10. The road workers\nhave done some good work on\nthe road running north from\nClias. Bison\u2019s.\nC. W. Steinberg made a busi\nness trip to Rogers Wednesday ot\nlast week.\nTwo of Alva Haines' children\nare quite sick at this writing.\nA goodly number of the neigh\nborhood friends of Aunt Tillit\nAaron surprised her last Satur\nday morning. All arrived with\nwell tilled baskets and a bounte\nous dinner was served. A gow*\nsocial ,ime was enjoyed. It wa^\nher seventieth birthday.\nMrs. Grace Steinberg lias beer\non the sick list this week.\nSome of our wide-a-wake far\nmers are plowing since the rain.\n1 Mari.\nIt is said that every man has\nhis double, even the single man.","height":"30516","width":"20964"}}
